# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: xml-rpc
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:xml-rpc/http] HTTP is a request–response protocol in the client–server model.
[src:xml-rpc/http] A transaction starts with a client submitting a request to the server, the server attempts to satisfy the request and returns a response to the client that describes the disposition of the request and optionally contains a requested resource such as an HTML document or other content.
[src:xml-rpc/http] In a common scenario, a web browser acts as the client, and a web server, hosting one or more websites, is the server.
[src:xml-rpc/http] A web browser is an example of a user agent (UA).
[src:xml-rpc/http] Other types of user agent include the indexing software used by search providers (web crawlers), voice browsers, mobile apps, and other software that accesses, consumes, or displays web content.
[src:xml-rpc/http] HTTP is designed to permit intermediate network elements to improve or enable communications between clients and servers.
[src:xml-rpc/http] High-traffic websites often benefit from web cache servers that deliver content on behalf of upstream servers to improve response time.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Web browsers cache previously accessed web resources and reuse them, whenever possible, to reduce network traffic.
[src:xml-rpc/http] HTTP proxy servers at private network boundaries can facilitate communication for clients without a globally routable address, by relaying messages with external servers.
[src:xml-rpc/http] To allow intermediate HTTP nodes (proxy servers, web caches, etc.) to accomplish their functions, some of the HTTP headers (found in HTTP requests/responses) are managed hop-by-hop whereas other HTTP headers are managed end-to-end (managed only by the source client and by the target web server).
[src:xml-rpc/http] A web resource is located by a uniform resource locator (URL), using the Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) schemes *http* and *https*.
[src:xml-rpc/http] URIs are encoded as hyperlinks in HTML documents, so as to form interlinked hypertext documents.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The protocol has been revised over time.
[src:xml-rpc/http] A version is identified as HTTP/# where # is the version number.
[src:xml-rpc/http] This article covers aspects of all versions but provides primary coverage for HTTP/0.9, HTTP/1.0, and HTTP/1.1.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Separate articles cover HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 in detail.
[src:xml-rpc/http] In HTTP/1.0, a separate TCP connection to the same server is made for every resource request.
[src:xml-rpc/http] In HTTP/1.1, instead a TCP connection can be reused to make multiple resource requests (i.e. of HTML pages, frames, images, scripts, stylesheets, etc.).
[src:xml-rpc/http] HTTP/1.1 communications therefore experience less latency as the establishment of TCP connections presents considerable overhead, especially under high traffic conditions.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Enhancements added with HTTP/2 allow for less latency and, in most cases, higher speeds than HTTP/1.1 communications.
[src:xml-rpc/http] HTTP/3 uses QUIC + UDP transport protocols instead of TCP.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Only the IP layer is used (which UDP, like TCP, builds on).
[src:xml-rpc/http] This slightly improves the average speed of communications and avoids the occasional problem of TCP connection congestion that can temporarily block or slow down the data flow of all its streams (another form of "*head of line blocking*").
[src:xml-rpc/http] HTTP/2 is supported by 71% of websites (34.1% HTTP/2 + 36.9% HTTP/3 with backwards compatibility) and supported by almost all web browsers (over 98% of users).
[src:xml-rpc/http] It is also supported by major web servers over Transport Layer Security (TLS) using an Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation (ALPN) extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required.
[src:xml-rpc/http] HTTP/3 is used on 36.9% of websites and is supported by most web browsers, i.e.
[src:xml-rpc/http] (at least partially) supported by 97% of users.
[src:xml-rpc/http] HTTP/3 uses QUIC instead of TCP for the underlying transport protocol.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Like HTTP/2, it does not obsolete previous major versions of the protocol.
[src:xml-rpc/http] In 2019, support for HTTP/3 was first added to Cloudflare and Chrome and also enabled in Firefox.
[src:xml-rpc/http] HTTP/3 has lower latency for real-world web pages and loads faster than HTTP/2, in some cases over three times faster than HTTP/1.1, which is still commonly the only protocol enabled.
[src:xml-rpc/http] HTTPS, the secure variant of HTTP, is used by more than 85% of websites.
[src:xml-rpc/http] HTTP presumes an underlying and reliable transport layer protocol.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The standard choice of the underlying protocol prior to HTTP/3 is Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:xml-rpc/http] HTTP/3 uses a different transport layer called QUIC, which provides reliability on top of the unreliable User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:xml-rpc/http] HTTP/1.1 and earlier have been adapted to be used over plain unreliable UDP in multicast and unicast situations, forming HTTPMU and HTTPU.
[src:xml-rpc/http] They are used in UPnP and Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP), two protocols usually run on a local area network.
[src:xml-rpc/http] HTTP is a stateless application-level protocol and it requires a reliable network transport connection to exchange data between client and server.
[src:xml-rpc/http] In HTTP implementations, TCP/IP connections are used using well-known ports (typically port 80 if the connection is unencrypted or port 443 if the connection is encrypted, see also List of TCP and UDP port numbers).
[src:xml-rpc/http] In HTTP/2, a TCP/IP connection plus multiple protocol channels are used.
[src:xml-rpc/http] In HTTP/3, the application transport protocol QUIC over UDP is used.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Data is exchanged through a sequence of request–response messages which are exchanged by a session layer transport connection.
[src:xml-rpc/http] An HTTP client initially tries to establish a connection, real or virtual, with a server.
[src:xml-rpc/http] An HTTP server listening on the port accepts the connection and then waits for a client's request message.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The client sends its HTTP request message.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Upon receiving the request the server sends back an HTTP response message, which includes header(s) plus a body if it is required.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The body of this response message is typically the requested resource, although an error message or other information may also be returned.
[src:xml-rpc/http] At any time and for many reasons, either the client or server can close the connection.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Closing a connection is usually advertised by one or more HTTP headers in the last request or response.
[src:xml-rpc/http] In HTTP/0.9, the TCP/IP connection is always closed after server response has been sent, so it is never persistent.
[src:xml-rpc/http] In HTTP/1.0, the TCP/IP connection should always be closed by server after a response has been sent.
[src:xml-rpc/http] In HTTP/1.1, a keep-alive-mechanism was officially introduced so that a connection could be reused for more than one request/response.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Such persistent connections reduce request latency perceptibly because the client does not need to re-negotiate the TCP 3-Way-Handshake connection after the first request has been sent.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Another positive side effect is that, in general, the connection becomes faster with time due to TCP's slow-start-mechanism.
[src:xml-rpc/http] HTTP/1.1 added also HTTP pipelining in order to further reduce lag time when using persistent connections by allowing clients to send multiple requests before waiting for each response.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Because of this, only HEAD and some GET requests (i.e. limited to real file requests and so with URLs without query string used as a command, etc.) could be pipelined in a safe and idempotent mode.
[src:xml-rpc/http] After many years of struggling with the problems introduced by enabling pipelining, this feature was first disabled and then removed from most browsers.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Pipelining was also removed because of the announced adoption of HTTP/2.
[src:xml-rpc/http] HTTP/2 extended the usage of persistent connections by multiplexing many concurrent requests/responses through a single TCP/IP connection.
[src:xml-rpc/http] HTTP/3 does not use TCP/IP connections but QUIC + UDP.
[src:xml-rpc/http] In HTTP/0.9, a requested resource was always sent in its entirety.
[src:xml-rpc/http] HTTP/1.0 added headers to manage resources cached by a client in order to allow conditional GET requests.
[src:xml-rpc/http] As a stateless protocol, HTTP does not require the web server to retain information or status about each user for the duration of multiple requests.
[src:xml-rpc/http] If a web application needs an application session, it implements it via HTTP cookies, hidden variables in a web form or another mechanism.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Typically, to start a session, an interactive login is performed, and to end a session, a logout is requested by the user.
[src:xml-rpc/http] These kind of operations use a custom authentication mechanism, not HTTP authentication.
[src:xml-rpc/http] HTTP provides multiple authentication schemes such as basic access authentication and digest access authentication which operate via a challenge–response mechanism whereby the server identifies and issues a challenge before serving the requested content.
[src:xml-rpc/http] HTTP provides a general framework for access control and authentication, via an extensible set of challenge–response authentication schemes, which can be used by a server to challenge a client request and by a client to provide authentication information.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The authentication mechanisms described above belong to the HTTP protocol and are managed by client and server HTTP software (if configured to require authentication before allowing client access to one or more web resources), and not by the web applications using an application session.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The HTTP authentication specification includes realms that provide an arbitrary, implementation-specific construct for further dividing resources common to a given root URI.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The realm value string, if present, is combined with the canonical root URI to form the protection space component of the challenge.
[src:xml-rpc/http] This in effect allows the server to define separate authentication scopes under one root URI.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The most popular way of establishing an encrypted HTTP connection is HTTPS.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Two other methods for establishing an encrypted HTTP connection also exist: Secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol, and using the HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header to specify an upgrade to TLS.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Browser support for these two is, however, nearly non-existent.
[src:xml-rpc/http] This section describes messages for HTTP/1.1.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Later versions, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3, use a binary protocol, where headers are encoded in a single `HEADERS` and zero or more `CONTINUATION` frames using HPACK (HTTP/2) or QPACK (HTTP/3), which both provide efficient header compression.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The request or response line from HTTP/1 has also been replaced by several pseudo-header fields, each beginning with a colon (`:`).
[src:xml-rpc/http] At the highest level, a message consists of a header followed by a body.
[src:xml-rpc/http] A header consists of lines of ASCII text; each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Structured data that differs for request vs. response.
[src:xml-rpc/http] lines (at least 1 for HTTP/1.1); see below.
[src:xml-rpc/http] A body consists of data in any format; not limited to ASCII.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The format must match that specified by the `Content-Type` header field if the message contains one.
[src:xml-rpc/http] A body is optional or, in other words, can be blank.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Before HTTP/2, the term *entity* was used to mean the body plus header fields that describe the body.
[src:xml-rpc/http] In particular, not all headers were considered part of the entity.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The term *entity header* referred to a header that was considered part of the entity, and sometimes the body was called the *entity body*.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Modern documentation uses *body* and *header* without using *entity*.
[src:xml-rpc/http] A header field represents metadata about the containing message.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Generally, the information of a header field is used by software and not shown to the user.
[src:xml-rpc/http] A header field line is formatted as a name-value pair with a colon separator.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Whitespace is not allowed around the name, but leading and trailing whitespace is ignored for the value part.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Unlike a method name that must match exactly (case-sensitive), a header field name is matched ignoring case although often shown with each word capitalized.
[src:xml-rpc/http] For example, the following are header fields for `Host` and `Accept-Language`.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The standards do not limit the size of a header field or the number of fields in a message.
[src:xml-rpc/http] However, most servers, clients, and proxy software impose limits for practical and security reasons.
[src:xml-rpc/http] For example, the Apache 2.3 server by default limits the size of each field to 8190 bytes, and there can be at most 100 header fields in a single request.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Although deprecated by RFC 7230, in the past, long lines could be split into multiple lines with a continuation line starting with a space or tab character.
[src:xml-rpc/http] A request is sent by a client to a server.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The start line includes a method name, a request URI and the protocol version with a single space between each field.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Request header fields allow the client to pass additional information beyond the request line, acting as request modifiers (similarly to the parameters of a procedure).
[src:xml-rpc/http] They give information about the client, about the target resource, or about the expected handling of the request.
[src:xml-rpc/http] In the HTTP/1.1 protocol, all header fields except `Host` are optional.
[src:xml-rpc/http] A request line containing only the path name is accepted by servers to maintain compatibility with HTTP clients before the HTTP/1.0 specification in RFC 1945.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The protocol structures transaction as operating on resources.
[src:xml-rpc/http] What a resource represents, whether pre-existing data or data that is generated dynamically, depends on the implementation of the server.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Often, the resource corresponds to a file or the output of an executable running on the server.
[src:xml-rpc/http] A request identifies a method (sometimes informally called *verb*) to classify the desired action to be performed on a resource.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The HTTP/1.0 specification defined the GET, HEAD, and POST methods as well as listing the PUT, DELETE, LINK and UNLINK methods under additional methods.
[src:xml-rpc/http] However, the HTTP/1.1 specification added five new methods: PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, and TRACE.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Any client can use any method and the server can be configured to support any combination of methods.
[src:xml-rpc/http] If a method is unknown to an intermediate, it will be treated as an unsafe and non-idempotent method.
[src:xml-rpc/http] There is no limit to the number of methods that can be defined, which allows for future methods to be specified without breaking existing infrastructure.
[src:xml-rpc/http] For example, WebDAV defined seven new methods and RFC 5789 specified the PATCH method.
[src:xml-rpc/http] A general-purpose web server is required to implement at least GET and HEAD, and all other methods are considered optional by the specification.
[src:xml-rpc/http] This is in contrast to HTTP header field names which are case-insensitive.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The request is for a representation of a resource.
[src:xml-rpc/http] include the representation data in the body.
[src:xml-rpc/http] in the response header, without having to transfer the entire representation.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The request is to process a resource in some way.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The request is to create or update a resource with the state in the request.
[src:xml-rpc/http] A distinction from POST is that the client specifies the target location on the server.
[src:xml-rpc/http] to the origin server identified by the request target.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Request is for a report of the HTTP methods that are supported for a resource.
[src:xml-rpc/http] This can be used to check the functionality of a web server by requesting '*' instead of a specific resource.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Requests the server to respond with the received request in the response body.
[src:xml-rpc/http] That way a client can see what (if any) changes or additions have been made by intermediaries.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The request is to modify a resource according to its partial state in the request.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Compared to PUT, this can save bandwidth by sending only part of a resource's representation instead of all of it.
[src:xml-rpc/http] A request method is *safe* if a request with that method has no intended effect on the server.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The methods GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, and TRACE are defined as safe.
[src:xml-rpc/http] In other words, safe methods are intended to be read-only.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Safe methods can still have side effects not seen by the client, such as appending request information to a log file or charging an advertising account.
[src:xml-rpc/http] In contrast, the methods POST, PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, and PATCH are not safe.
[src:xml-rpc/http] They may modify the state of the server or have other effects such as sending an email.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Such methods are therefore not usually used by conforming web robots or web crawlers; some that do not conform tend to make requests without regard to context or consequences.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Despite the prescribed safety of GET requests, in practice their handling by the server is not technically limited in any way.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Careless or deliberately irregular programming can allow GET requests to cause non-trivial changes on the server.
[src:xml-rpc/http] This is discouraged because of the problems which can occur when web caching, search engines, and other automated agents make unintended changes on the server.
[src:xml-rpc/http] For example, a website might allow deletion of a resource through a URL such as *https://example.com/article/1234/delete*, which, if arbitrarily fetched, even using GET, would simply delete the article.
[src:xml-rpc/http] A properly coded website would require a DELETE or POST method for this action, which non-malicious bots would not make.
[src:xml-rpc/http] One example of this occurring in practice was during the short-lived Google Web Accelerator beta, which prefetched arbitrary URLs on the page a user was viewing, causing records to be automatically altered or deleted *en masse*.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The beta was suspended only weeks after its first release, following widespread criticism.
[src:xml-rpc/http] A request method is *idempotent* if multiple identical requests with that method have the same effect as a single such request.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The methods PUT and DELETE, and safe methods are defined as idempotent.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Safe methods are trivially idempotent, since they are intended to have no effect on the server whatsoever; the PUT and DELETE methods, meanwhile, are idempotent since successive identical requests will be ignored.
[src:xml-rpc/http] A website might, for instance, set up a PUT endpoint to modify a user's recorded email address.
[src:xml-rpc/http] If this endpoint is configured correctly, any requests which ask to change a user's email address to the same email address which is already recorded—e.g. duplicate requests following a successful request—will have no effect.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Similarly, a request to DELETE a certain user will have no effect if that user has already been deleted.
[src:xml-rpc/http] In contrast, the methods POST, CONNECT, and PATCH are not necessarily idempotent, and therefore sending an identical POST request multiple times may further modify the state of the server or have further effects, such as sending multiple emails.
[src:xml-rpc/http] In some cases this is the desired effect, but in other cases it may occur accidentally.
[src:xml-rpc/http] A user might, for example, inadvertently send multiple POST requests by clicking a button again if they were not given clear feedback that the first click was being processed.
[src:xml-rpc/http] While web browsers may show alert dialog boxes to warn users in some cases where reloading a page may re-submit a POST request, it is generally up to the web application to handle cases where a POST request should not be submitted more than once.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Note that whether or not a method is idempotent is not enforced by the protocol or web server.
[src:xml-rpc/http] It is perfectly possible to write a web application in which (for example) a database insert or other non-idempotent action is triggered by a GET or other request.
[src:xml-rpc/http] To do so against recommendations, however, may result in undesirable consequences, if a user agent assumes that repeating the same request is safe when it is not.
[src:xml-rpc/http] A request method is *cacheable* if responses to requests with that method may be stored for future reuse.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The methods GET, HEAD, and POST are defined as cacheable.
[src:xml-rpc/http] In contrast, the methods PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, TRACE, and PATCH are not cacheable.
[src:xml-rpc/http] A response is sent to the client by the server.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The start line of a response consists of the protocol version, a status code and optionally a reason phrase with fields separated by a single space character.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The following response start line specifies protocol version `HTTP/1.1`, status code `400` and reason phrase `Bad Request`.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Response header fields allow the server to pass additional information beyond the status line, acting as response modifiers.
[src:xml-rpc/http] They give information about the server or about further access to the target resource or related resources.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Each response header field has a defined meaning which can be further refined by the semantics of the request method or response status code.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The status code is a three-digit, decimal, integer value that represents the disposition of the server's attempt to satisfy the client's request.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Generally, a client handles a response primarily based on the status code and secondarily on response header fields.
[src:xml-rpc/http] A client may not understand each status code that a server reports but it must understand the class as indicated by the first digit and treat an unrecognized code as equivalent to the x00 code of that class.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The request was received, continuing process.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The request was successfully received, understood, and accepted.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Further action needs to be taken in order to complete the request.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The request cannot be fulfilled due to an issue that the client might be able to control.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The server failed to fulfill an apparently valid request.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The standard reason phrases are only recommendations.
[src:xml-rpc/http] A web server is allowed to use a localized equivalent.
[src:xml-rpc/http] If a status code indicates a problem, the user agent might display the reason phrase to the user to provide further information about the nature of the problem.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The standard also allows the user agent to attempt to interpret the reason phrase, though this might be unwise since the standard explicitly specifies that status codes are machine-readable and reason phrases are human-readable.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The following demonstrates an HTTP/1.1 request-response transaction for a server at www.example.com, port 80.
[src:xml-rpc/http] HTTP/1.0 would use the same messages except for a few missing headers.
[src:xml-rpc/http] HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 would use the same request-response mechanism but with different representations for HTTP headers.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The following is a request with no body.
[src:xml-rpc/http] It consists of a start line, 6 header fields and a blank line – each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The `Host` header field distinguishes between various DNS names sharing a single IP address, allowing name-based virtual hosting.
[src:xml-rpc/http] While optional in HTTP/1.0, it is mandatory in HTTP/1.1.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Although not clear in the representation above (due to limitations of this wiki), the blank line at the end results in ending in two line terminator sequences.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Represented as a stream of characters, a shorted version of above shows this more clearly with `<CRLF>` representing a line terminator sequence: `GET / HTTP/1.1<CRLF>Host: www.example.com<CRLF><CRLF>`.
[src:xml-rpc/http] In the following response, the ETag (entity tag) header field is used to determine if a cached version of the requested resource is identical to the current version of the resource on the server.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The `Content-Type` header field specifies the Internet media type of the data conveyed by the HTTP message, and `Content-Length` indicates its length in bytes.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The HTTP/1.1 webserver publishes its ability to respond to requests for a byte range of the resource by including `Accept-Ranges: bytes`.
[src:xml-rpc/http] This is useful, if the client needs to have only certain portions of a resource sent by the server, which is called byte serving.
[src:xml-rpc/http] When `Connection: close` is sent, it means that the web server will close the TCP connection immediately after the end of the transfer of this response.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Most of the header fields are optional but some are mandatory.
[src:xml-rpc/http] When header `Content-Length` is missing from a response with a body, then this should be considered an error in HTTP/1.0 but it may not be an error in HTTP/1.1 if header `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` is present.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Chunked transfer encoding uses a chunk size of 0 to mark the end of the content.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Some old implementations of HTTP/1.0 omitted the header `Content-Length` when the length of the body was not known at the beginning of the response and so the transfer of data to client continued until server closed the socket.
[src:xml-rpc/http] `Content-Encoding: gzip` informs the client that the body is compressed per the gzip algorithm.
[src:xml-rpc/http] A content delivery protocol that was displaced by HTTP in the early 1990s.
[src:xml-rpc/http] A Gopher-inspired protocol which mandates privacy-related features.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Tim Berners-Lee and his team at CERN are credited with inventing HTTP, along with HTML and the associated technology for a web server and a client user interface called web browser.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Berners-Lee designed HTTP in order to help with the adoption of his other idea: the "WorldWideWeb" project, which was first proposed in 1989, now known as the World Wide Web.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Development of HTTP was initiated in 1989 and summarized in a simple document describing the behavior of a client and a server using the first HTTP version, named 0.9.
[src:xml-rpc/http] That version was subsequently developed, eventually becoming the public 1.0.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Development of early HTTP Request for Comments (RFC) documents started a few years later in a coordinated effort by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), with work later moving to the IETF.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The protocol used had only one method, namely GET, which would request a page from a server.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The response from the server was always an HTML page.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Since 1992, a new document was written to specify the evolution of the basic protocol towards its next full version.
[src:xml-rpc/http] It supported both the simple request method of the 0.9 version and the full GET request that included the client HTTP version.
[src:xml-rpc/http] This was the first of the many unofficial HTTP/1.0 drafts that preceded the final work on HTTP/1.0.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The HTTP WG planned to revise and publish new versions of the protocol as HTTP/1.0 and HTTP/1.1 within 1995, but, because of the many revisions, that timeline lasted much more than one year.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The HTTP WG planned also to specify a far future version of HTTP called HTTP-NG (HTTP Next Generation) that would have solved all remaining problems, of previous versions, related to performances, low latency responses, etc. but this work started only a few years later and it was never completed.
[src:xml-rpc/http] In May 1996, RFC 1945 was published as a final HTTP/1.0 revision of what had been used in previous 4 years as a pre-standard HTTP/1.0-draft which was already used by many web browsers and web servers.
[src:xml-rpc/http] In early 1996 developers started to even include unofficial extensions of the HTTP/1.0 protocol (i.e. keep-alive connections, etc.) into their products by using drafts of the upcoming HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Since early 1996, major web browsers and web server developers also started to implement new features specified by pre-standard HTTP/1.1 drafts specifications.
[src:xml-rpc/http] End-user adoption of the new versions of browsers and servers was rapid.
[src:xml-rpc/http] In March 1996, one web hosting company reported that over 40% of browsers in use on the Internet used the new HTTP/1.1 header "Host" to enable virtual hosting, and that by June 1996, 65% of all browsers accessing their servers were pre-standard HTTP/1.1 compliant.
[src:xml-rpc/http] In January 1997, RFC 2068 was officially released as HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:xml-rpc/http] In June 1999, RFC 2616 was released to include all improvements and updates based on previous (obsolete) HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Resuming the old 1995 plan of previous HTTP Working Group, in 1997 an *HTTP-NG Working Group* was formed to develop a new HTTP protocol named HTTP-NG (HTTP New Generation).
[src:xml-rpc/http] A few proposals / drafts were produced for the new protocol to use multiplexing of HTTP transactions inside a single TCP/IP connection, but in 1999, the group stopped its activity passing the technical problems to IETF.
[src:xml-rpc/http] In 2007, the IETF HTTP Working Group (HTTP WG bis or HTTPbis) was restarted firstly to revise and clarify previous HTTP/1.1 specifications and secondly to write and refine future HTTP/2 specifications (named httpbis).
[src:xml-rpc/http] In 2009, Google announced SPDY – a binary protocol they developed to speed up web traffic between browsers and servers.
[src:xml-rpc/http] In many tests, using SPDY was indeed faster than using HTTP/1.1.
[src:xml-rpc/http] SPDY was integrated into Google's Chromium and then into other major web browsers.
[src:xml-rpc/http] Some of the ideas about multiplexing HTTP streams over a single TCP connection were taken from various sources, including the work of W3C HTTP-NG Working Group.
[src:xml-rpc/http] In 2012, HTTP Working Group (HTTPbis) announced the need for a new protocol; initially considering aspects of SPDY and eventually deciding to derive the new protocol from SPDY.
[src:xml-rpc/http] In May 2015, HTTP/2 was published as RFC 7540.
[src:xml-rpc/http] The protocol was quickly adopted by web browsers already supporting SPDY and more slowly by web servers.
[src:xml-rpc/http] As of 2022, HTTP/0.9 support has not been officially, completely deprecated and is still present in many web servers and browsers (for server responses only), even if usually disabled.
[src:xml-rpc/http] It is unclear how long it will take to decommission HTTP/0.9.
[src:xml-rpc/http] In 2020, the first drafts of HTTP/3 were published and major web browsers and web servers started to adopt it.
[src:xml-rpc/http] On 6 June 2022, IETF standardized HTTP/3 as RFC 9114.
[src:xml-rpc/http] In June 2022, RFC documents were published that deprecated many of the previous documents and introducing a few minor changes and a refactoring of HTTP semantics description into a separate document.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] In computer science, **marshalling** or **marshaling** (US spelling) is the process of transforming the memory representation of an object into a data format suitable for storage or transmission, especially between different runtimes.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] It is typically used when data must be moved between different parts of a computer program or from one program to another.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling simplifies complex communications, because it allows using *composite objects* instead of being restricted to *primitive objects*.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling is sometimes used as synonymous with serializing, while serialization is actually one step in the process of marshalling an object.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling and serialization might thus be done differently, although some form of serialization is usually used to do marshalling.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] The term *deserialization* is somewhat similar to *un*-marshalling a dry object "on the server side", i.e., demarshalling (or unmarshalling) to get a live object back: the serialized object is transformed into an internal data structure, i.e., a live object within the target runtime.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] It usually corresponds to the exact inverse process of marshalling, although sometimes both ends of the process trigger specific business logic.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] The accurate definition of marshalling differs across programming languages such as Python, Java, and .NET, and in some contexts, is used interchangeably with serialization.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] To "serialize" an object means to convert its state into a byte stream in such a way that the byte stream may be converted back into a copy of the object, which is unmarshalling in essence.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] Different programming languages either make or don’t make the distinction between the two concepts.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] In the Java-related RFC 2713, marshalling is used when serializing objects for remote invocation.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] An object that is marshalled records the state of the original object and it contains the codebase (*codebase* here refers to a list of URLs where the object code can be loaded from, and not source code).
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] Hence, in order to convert the object state and codebase(s), unmarshalling must be done.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] The unmarshaller interface automatically converts the marshalled data containing codebase(s) into an executable Java object in JAXB.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] Any object that can be deserialized can be unmarshalled.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling is used within implementations of different remote procedure call (RPC) mechanisms, where it is necessary to transport data between processes and/or between threads.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] In Microsoft's Component Object Model (COM), interface pointers must be marshalled when crossing COM apartment boundaries.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] In the .NET Framework, the conversion between an unmanaged type and a CLR type, as in the P/Invoke process, is also an example of an action that requires marshalling to take place.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] Additionally, marshalling is used extensively within scripts and applications that use the XPCOM technologies provided within the Mozilla application framework.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] The Mozilla Firefox browser is a popular application built with this framework, that additionally allows scripting languages to use XPCOM through XPConnect (Cross-Platform Connect).
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] In the Microsoft Windows family of operating systems the entire set of device drivers for Direct3D are kernel-mode drivers.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] The user-mode portion of the API is handled by the DirectX runtime provided by Microsoft.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] This is an issue because calling kernel-mode operations from user-mode requires performing a system call, and this inevitably forces the CPU to switch to "kernel mode".
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] This is a slow operation, taking on the order of microseconds to complete.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] During this time, the CPU is unable to perform any operations.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] As such, minimizing the number of times this switching operation must be performed would optimize performance to a substantive degree.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] Linux OpenGL drivers are split in two: a kernel-driver and a user-space driver.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] The user-space driver does all the translation of OpenGL commands into machine code to be submitted to the GPU.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] To reduce the number of system calls, the user-space driver implements marshalling.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] If the GPU's command buffer is full of rendering data, the API could simply store the requested rendering call in a temporary buffer and, when the command buffer is close to being empty, it can perform a switch to kernel-mode and add a number of stored commands all at once.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling data requires some kind of data transfer, which leverages a specific data format to be chosen as the serialization target.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] XML is one such format and means of transferring data between systems.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] Microsoft, for example, uses it as the basis of the file formats of the various components (Word, Excel, Access, PowerPoint, etc.) of the Microsoft Office suite (see Office Open XML).
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] While this typically results in a verbose wire format, XML's fully-bracketed "start-tag", "end-tag" syntax allows provision of more accurate diagnostics and easier recovery from transmission or disk errors.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] In addition, because the tags occur repeatedly, one can use standard compression methods to shrink the content—all the Office file formats are created by zipping the raw XML.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] Alternative formats such as JSON (JavaScript Object Notation) are more concise, but correspondingly less robust for error recovery.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] Once the data is transferred to a program or an application, it needs to be converted back to an object for usage.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] Hence, unmarshalling is generally used in the receiver end of the implementations of Remote Method Invocation (RMI) and Remote procedure call (RPC) mechanisms to unmarshal transmitted objects in an executable form.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] JAXB or Java Architecture for XML Binding is the most common framework used by developers to marshal and unmarshal Java objects.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] JAXB provides for the interconversion between fundamental data types supported by Java and standard XML schema data types.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] `System.Xml.Serialization.XmlSerializer` is the framework used by C# developers to marshal and unmarshal C# objects.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] One of the advantages of C# over Java is that C# natively supports marshalling due to the inclusion of `System.Xml.Serialization.XmlSerializer` class.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] Java, on the other hand requires a non-native glue code in the form of JAXB to support marshalling.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] An example of unmarshalling is the conversion of an XML representation of an object to the default representation of the object in any programming language.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] Unmarshalling is the process of converting the XML representation to the default executable Java representation, and running that very code to get a consistent, live object back.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] Had a different format been chosen, the unmarshalling process would have been different, but the end result in the target runtime would be the same.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] The process of unmarshalling XML data into an executable Java object is taken care of by the in-built `jakarta.xml.bind.Unmarshaller` (formally `javax.xml.bind.Unmarshaller`) class.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] The unmarshal methods defined in the `jakarta.xml.bind.Unmarshaller` class are overloaded to accept XML from different types of input such as a `java.io.File`, `java.io.FileInputStream`, or `java.net.URL`.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] Unmarshal methods can deserialize an entire XML document or a small part of it.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] When the XML root element is globally declared, these methods utilize the `jakarta.xml.bind.JAXBContext`'s mapping of XML root elements to JAXB mapped classes to initiate the unmarshalling.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] If the mappings are not sufficient and the root elements are declared locally, the unmarshal methods use `declaredType` methods for the unmarshalling process.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] These two approaches can be understood below.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] The unmarshal method uses `jakarta.xml.bind.JAXBContext` (formerly `javax.xml.bind.JAXBContext`) to unmarshal the XML data, when the root element is globally declared.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] The `jakarta.xml.bind.JAXBContext` object always maintains a mapping of the globally declared XML element and its name to a JAXB mapped class.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] If the XML element name or its `@xsi:type` attribute matches the JAXB mapped class, the unmarshal method transforms the XML data using the appropriate JAXB mapped class.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] However, if the XML element name has no match, the unmarshal process will abort and throw an `jakarta.xml.bind.UnmarshalException` (formerly `javax.xml.bind.UnmarshalException`).
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] This can be avoided by using the unmarshal by `declaredType` methods.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] When the root element is not declared globally, the application assists the unmarshaller by application-provided mapping using `declaredType` parameters.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] By an order of precedence, even if the root name has a mapping to an appropriate JAXB class, the `declaredType` overrides the mapping.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] However, if the `@xsi:type` attribute of the XML data has a mapping to an appropriate JAXB class, then this takes precedence over declaredType parameter.
[src:xml-rpc/marshalling-computer-science] The unmarshal methods by `declaredType` parameters always return a `jakarta.xml.bind.JAXBElement<T>` instance.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] That is, the programmer writes essentially the same code whether the subroutine is local to the executing program, or remote.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] This is a form of server interaction (caller is client, executor is server), typically implemented via a request–response message passing system.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] In the object-oriented programming paradigm, RPCs are represented by remote method invocation (RMI).
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] The RPC model implies a level of location transparency, namely that calling procedures are largely the same whether they are local or remote, but usually, they are not identical, so local calls can be distinguished from remote calls.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] Remote calls are usually orders of magnitude slower and less reliable than local calls, so distinguishing them is important.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] Many different (often incompatible) technologies have been used to implement the concept.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] Request–response protocols date to early distributed computing in the late 1960s, theoretical proposals of remote procedure calls as the model of network operations date to the 1970s, and practical implementations date to the early 1980s.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] Bruce Jay Nelson is generally credited with coining the term "remote procedure call" in 1981.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] Remote procedure calls used in modern operating systems trace their roots back to the RC 4000 multiprogramming system, which used a request-response communication protocol for process synchronization.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] The idea of treating network operations as remote procedure calls goes back at least to the 1970s in early ARPANET documents.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] In 1978, Per Brinch Hansen proposed Distributed Processes, a language for distributed computing based on "external requests" consisting of procedure calls between processes.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] One of the earliest practical implementations was in 1982 by Brian Randell and colleagues for their Newcastle Connection between UNIX machines.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] This was soon followed by "Lupine" by Andrew Birrell and Bruce Nelson in the Cedar environment at Xerox PARC.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] Lupine automatically generated stubs, providing type-safe bindings, and used an efficient protocol for communication.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] One of the first business uses of RPC was by Xerox under the name "Courier" in 1981.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] The first popular implementation of RPC on Unix was Sun's RPC (now called ONC RPC), used as the basis for Network File System (NFS).
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] In the 1990s, with the popularity of object-oriented programming, an alternative model of remote method invocation (RMI) was widely implemented, such as in Common Object Request Broker Architecture (CORBA, 1991) and Java remote method invocation.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] RMIs, in turn, fell in popularity with the rise of the internet, particularly in the 2000s.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] An RPC is initiated by the *client*, which sends a request message to a known remote *server* to execute a specified procedure with supplied parameters.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] The remote server sends a response to the client, and the application continues its process.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] While the server is processing the call, the client is blocked (it waits until the server has finished processing before resuming execution), unless the client sends an asynchronous request to the server, such as an XMLHttpRequest.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] There are many variations and subtleties in various implementations, resulting in a variety of different (incompatible) RPC protocols.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] An important difference between remote procedure calls and local calls is that remote calls can fail because of unpredictable network problems.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] Also, callers generally must deal with such failures without knowing whether the remote procedure was actually invoked.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] Idempotent procedures (those that have no additional effects if called more than once) are easily handled, but enough difficulties remain that code to call remote procedures is often confined to carefully written low-level subsystems.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] The client stub packs the parameters into a message and makes a system call to send the message.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] Packing the parameters is called marshalling.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] The client's local operating system sends the message from the client machine to the server machine.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] The local operating system on the server machine passes the incoming packets to the server stub.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] The server stub unpacks the parameters from the message.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] Unpacking the parameters is called unmarshalling.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] Finally, the server stub calls the server procedure.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] The reply traces the same steps in the reverse direction.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] To let different clients access servers, a number of standardized RPC systems have been created.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] Most of these use an interface description language (IDL) to let various platforms call the RPC.
[src:xml-rpc/remote-procedure-call] The IDL files can then be used to generate code to interface between the client and servers.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] In a web service, a web technology such as HTTP is used for transferring machine-readable file formats such as XML and JSON.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] In practice, a web service commonly provides an object-oriented web-based interface to a database server, utilized for example by another web server, or by a mobile app, that provides a user interface to the end-user.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] Many organizations that provide data in formatted HTML pages will also provide that data on their server as XML or JSON, often through a Web service to allow syndication.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] Another application offered to the end-user may be a mashup, where a Web server consumes several Web services at different machines and compiles the content into one user interface.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] Asynchronous JavaScript and XML (AJAX) is a dominant technology for Web services.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] Developing from the combination of HTTP servers, JavaScript clients and Plain Old XML (as distinct from SOAP and W3C Web Services), now it is frequently used with JSON as well as, or instead of, XML.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] Representational State Transfer (REST) is an architecture for well-behaved Web services that can function at Internet scale.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] A Web API is a development in Web services where emphasis has been moving to simpler representational state transfer (REST) based communications.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] Restful APIs do not require XML-based Web service protocols (SOAP and WSDL) to support their interfaces.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] W3C Web Services may use SOAP over HTTP protocol, allowing less costly (more efficient) interactions over the Internet than via proprietary solutions like EDI/B2B.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] Besides SOAP over HTTP, Web services can also be implemented on other reliable transport mechanisms like FTP.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] The term "Web service" describes a standardized way of integrating Web-based applications using the XML, SOAP, WSDL and UDDI open standards over an Internet Protocol backbone.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] XML is the data format used to contain the data and provide metadata around it, SOAP is used to transfer the data, WSDL is used for describing the services available and UDDI lists what services are available.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] A Web service is a method of communication between two electronic devices over a network.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] It is a software function provided at a network address over the Web with the service *always-on* as in the concept of utility computing.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] Many organizations use multiple software systems for management.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] Different software systems often need to exchange data with each other, and a Web service is a method of communication that allows two software systems to exchange this data over the Internet.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] The software system that requests data is called a *service requester*, whereas the software system that would process the request and provide the data is called a *service provider*.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] Different software may use different programming languages, and hence there is a need for a method of data exchange that doesn't depend upon a particular programming language.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] Most types of software can, however, interpret XML tags.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] Thus, Web services can use XML files for data exchange.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] All of these rules for communication are defined in a file called WSDL (Web Services Description Language), which has a `.wsdl` extension.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] A directory called UDDI (Universal Description, Discovery, and Integration) defines which software system should be contacted for which type of data.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] So when one software system needs one particular report/data, it would go to the UDDI and find out which other systems it can contact for receiving that data.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] Once the software system finds out which other systems it should contact, it would then contact that system using a special protocol called SOAP (Simple Object Access Protocol).
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] The service provider system would first validate the data request by referring to the WSDL file, and then process the request and send the data under the SOAP protocol.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] Automated tools can aid in the creation of a Web service.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] For services using WSDL, it is possible to either automatically generate WSDL for existing classes (a bottom-up model) or to generate a class skeleton given existing WSDL (a top-down model).
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] Critics of non-RESTful Web services often complain that they are too complex and based upon large software vendors or integrators, rather than typical open source implementations.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] There are also concerns about performance due to Web services' use of XML as a message format and SOAP/HTTP in enveloping and transporting.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] Functional and non-functional testing of Web services is done with the help of WSDL parsing.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] Regression testing is performed by identifying the changes made to upgrade software.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] Web service regression testing needs can be categorized in three different ways, namely, changes in WSDL, changes in the code, and selective re-testing of operations.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] We can capture the above three needs in three intermediate forms of Subset WSDL, namely, Difference WSDL (DWSDL), Unit WSDL (UWSDL), and Reduced WSDL (RWSDL), respectively.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] These three Subset WSDLs are then combined to form Combined WSDL (CWSDL) that is further used for regression testing of the Web service.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] This will help in Automated Web Service Change Management (AWSCM), by performing the selection of the relevant test cases to construct a reduced test suite from the old test suite.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] Web services testing can also be automated using several test automation tools like SoapUI, Oracle Application Testing Suite (OATS), Unified Functional Testing, Selenium, etc.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] Work-related to the capture and visualization of changes made to a Web service.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] Visualization and computation of changes can be done in the form of intermediate artifacts (Subset WSDL).
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] The insight on the computation of change impact is helpful in testing, top-down development and reduce regression testing.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] AWSCM is a tool that can identify subset operations in a WSDL file to construct a subset WSDL.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] While UDDI was intended to serve as a service directory and become the means to discovering web services, many vendors discontinued their UDDI solutions or repositories between 2005 and 2008, including Microsoft, SAP, IBM, among others.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] A key study published in WWW2008 Conference (Beijing, China) presented the state of SOAP-based web services and concluded that only 63% of the available SOAP-based web services at the time of the study were actually active or can be invoked.
[src:xml-rpc/web-service] The study also found that search engines were becoming an ideal source for searching for web services compared to that of service registries like the UDDI due its design complexity.
[src:xml-rpc/xml-rpc] The XML-RPC protocol was created in 1998 by Dave Winer of UserLand Software and Microsoft, with Microsoft seeing the protocol as an essential part of scaling up its efforts in business-to-business e-commerce.
[src:xml-rpc/xml-rpc] As new functionality was introduced, the standard evolved into what is now SOAP.
[src:xml-rpc/xml-rpc] UserLand supported XML-RPC from version 5.1 of its Frontier web content management system, released in June 1998.
[src:xml-rpc/xml-rpc] XML-RPC's idea of a human-readable-and-writable, script-parsable standard for HTTP-based requests and responses has also been implemented in competing specifications such as Allaire's Web Distributed Data Exchange (WDDX) and webMethod's Web Interface Definition Language (WIDL).
[src:xml-rpc/xml-rpc] Prior art wrapping COM, CORBA, and Java RMI objects in XML syntax and transporting them via HTTP also existed in DataChannel's WebBroker technology.
[src:xml-rpc/xml-rpc] The generic use of XML for remote procedure call (RPC) was patented by Phillip Merrick, Stewart Allen, and Joseph Lapp in April 2006, claiming benefit to a provisional application filed in March 1998.
[src:xml-rpc/xml-rpc] The patent was assigned to webMethods, located in Fairfax, Virginia.
[src:xml-rpc/xml-rpc] In XML-RPC, a client performs an RPC by sending an HTTP request to a server that implements XML-RPC and receives the HTTP response.
[src:xml-rpc/xml-rpc] A call can have multiple parameters and one result.
[src:xml-rpc/xml-rpc] The protocol defines a few data types for the parameters and result.
[src:xml-rpc/xml-rpc] Some of these data types are complex, i.e. nested.
[src:xml-rpc/xml-rpc] For example, you can have a parameter that is an array of five integers.
[src:xml-rpc/xml-rpc] The parameters/result structure and the set of data types are meant to mirror those used in common programming languages.
[src:xml-rpc/xml-rpc] In comparison to RESTful protocols, where *resource representations* (documents) are transferred, XML-RPC is designed to *call methods*.
[src:xml-rpc/xml-rpc] The practical difference is just that XML-RPC is much more structured, which means common library code can be used to implement clients and servers and there is less design and documentation work for a specific application protocol.
[src:xml-rpc/xml-rpc] One salient technical difference between typical RESTful protocols and XML-RPC is that many RESTful protocols use the HTTP URI for parameter information, whereas with XML-RPC, the URI just identifies the server.
[src:xml-rpc/xml-rpc] Recent critics (from 2010 and onwards) of XML-RPC argue that RPC calls can be made with plain XML, and that XML-RPC does not add any value over XML.
[src:xml-rpc/xml-rpc] Both XML-RPC and XML require an application-level data model, such as which field names are defined in the XML schema or the parameter names in XML-RPC.
[src:xml-rpc/xml-rpc] Furthermore, XML-RPC uses about 4 times the number of bytes compared to plain XML to encode the same objects, which is itself verbose compared to JSON.
[src:xml-rpc/xml] The design goals of XML emphasize simplicity, generality, and usability across the Internet.
[src:xml-rpc/xml] It is a textual data format with strong support via Unicode for different human languages.
[src:xml-rpc/xml] Although the design of XML focuses on documents, the language is widely used for the representation of arbitrary data structures, such as those used in web services.
[src:xml-rpc/xml] Several schema systems exist to aid in the definition of XML-based languages, while programmers have developed many application programming interfaces (APIs) to aid the processing of XML data.
[src:xml-rpc/xml] The main purpose of XML is serialization, i.e. storing, transmitting, and reconstructing arbitrary data.
[src:xml-rpc/xml] For two disparate systems to exchange information, they need to agree upon a file format.
[src:xml-rpc/xml] It is therefore analogous to a lingua franca for representing information.
[src:xml-rpc/xml] As a markup language, XML labels, categorizes, and structurally organizes information.
[src:xml-rpc/xml] XML tags represent the data structure and contain metadata.
[src:xml-rpc/xml] What is within the tags is data, encoded in the way the XML standard specifies.
[src:xml-rpc/xml] An additional XML schema (XSD) defines the necessary metadata for interpreting and validating XML.
[src:xml-rpc/xml] (This is also referred to as the canonical schema.) An XML document that adheres to basic XML rules is "well-formed"; one that adheres to its schema is "valid".
[src:xml-rpc/xml] IETF RFC 7303 (which supersedes the older RFC 3023), provides rules for the construction of media types for use in XML message.
[src:xml-rpc/xml] It defines three media types: `application/xml` (`text/xml` is an alias), `application/xml-external-parsed-entity` (`text/xml-external-parsed-entity` is an alias) and `application/xml-dtd`.
[src:xml-rpc/xml] They are used for transmitting raw XML files without exposing their internal semantics.
[src:xml-rpc/xml] RFC 7303 further recommends that XML-based languages be given media types ending in `+xml`, for example, `image/svg+xml` for SVG.
[src:xml-rpc/xml] Further guidelines for the use of XML in a networked context appear in RFC 3470, also known as IETF BCP 70, a document covering many aspects of designing and deploying an XML-based language.
[src:xml-rpc/xml] XML has come into common use for the interchange of data over the Internet.
[src:xml-rpc/xml] Hundreds of document formats using XML syntax have been developed, including RSS, Atom, Office Open XML, OpenDocument, SVG, COLLADA, and XHTML.
[src:xml-rpc/xml] XML also provides the base language for communication protocols such as SOAP and XMPP.
[src:xml-rpc/xml] It is one of the message exchange formats used in the Asynchronous JavaScript and XML (AJAX) programming technique.
[src:xml-rpc/xml] Many industry data standards, such as Health Level 7, OpenTravel Alliance, FpML, MISMO, and the National Information Exchange Model are based on XML and the rich features of the XML schema specification.
[src:xml-rpc/xml] In publishing, Darwin Information Typing Architecture is an XML industry data standard.
[src:xml-rpc/xml] XML is used extensively to underpin various publishing formats.
[src:xml-rpc/xml] One of the applications of XML in science is the representation of operational meteorology information based on IWXXM standards.
[src:xml-rpc/xml] The material in this section is based on the XML Specification.
[src:xml-rpc/xml] This is not an exhaustive list of all the constructs that appear in XML; it provides an introduction to the key constructs most often encountered in day-to-day use.
[src:xml-rpc/xml] character (except Null) may appear in an (1.1) XML document (while some are discouraged).
[src:xml-rpc/xml] The specification places requirements on what an XML processor must do and not do, but the application is outside its scope.
[src:xml-rpc/xml] Strings of characters that are not markup are content.
[src:xml-rpc/xml] are classified as markup, while the text between them is classified as content.
[src:xml-rpc/xml] In addition, whitespace before and after the outermost element is classified as markup.
[src:xml-rpc/xml] is a logical document component that either begins with a start-tag and ends with a matching end-tag or consists only of an empty-element tag.
